ce:section.ce:para:
The practical detection potential of CdTe/CQDs@SiO2@MIPs sensor for CIP in seawater samples was further measured by recovery experiments. The actual seawater was not detected as containing CIP before spiking. The spiked concentrations of CIP in seawater samples were 5, 10 and 15 μmol L−1. The spiked recoveries of 96.2%–103.1% (Table 1
                        ) were obtained under the optimal detection conditions. Compared with other methods for the determination of CIP in different matrixes (Table 2
                        ), the CdTe/CQDs@SiO2@MIPs sensor was more convenient than the liquid chromatograph coupled detection method [40,41], smaller in detection range than electrochemical detection [43,44], and had a lower detection limit than the other detection methods [22,42,45]. Overall, the results showed that the CdTe/CQDs@SiO2@MIPs sensor had great potential for application and development in applications for CIP detection in ocean water.
